\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp. {\b acer}: Whole plant usually with dense, crispate hairs. 2n = 18. {\i Throughout most of the range of the species.}
\par 
\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp. {\b angulosus} (Gaudin) Vacc.,{\i  Cat. Rais. Pl. Vasc. Aoste }{\b 1}: 350 (1909): Leaves glabrous. Involucral bracts sparsely to moderately hairy, green with lilac apex.{\i  C. Europe}.
\par 
\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b c}) Subsp. {\b droebachiensis} (O. F. Mueller) Arcangeli,{\i  Comp. Fl. Ital.} 340 (1882): Leaves glabrous. Upper cauline leaves appreciably smaller than the basal, not ciliate. Capitula up to 30. Involucral bracts glabrous or almost so, about equalling the ligules.{\i  N.C. Europe, extending northwards to S. Norway}.
\par 
\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b d}) Subsp. {\b macrophyllus} (Herbich) Guterm., {\i Phyton }({\i Austria}) {\b 15}: 268 (1973): Leaves glabrous, the upper cauline not appreciably smaller than the basal, ciliate. Capitula usually 30-70. Involucral bracts glabrous or almost so, distinctly exceeding the ligules.{\i  Carpathians and E. Austria}.
\par 
\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b e}) Subsp. {\b politus} (Fries) H. Lindb. fil.,{\i  Enum. Pl. Fennoscand. Or.} 56 (1901) ({\i E. elongatus} Ledeb., non Moench): Leaves glabrous, usually shiny. Involucral bracts with a few eglandular hairs at the base, purplish. 2n = 18. {\i Fennoscandia and U.S.S.R. southwards to N. Ukraine}.
\par 
\pard\f0\fs28  Plants from the C. Alps have a weak, ascending habit quite unlike the normal erect habit; their status is uncertain.
