\pard\f0\fs28  {\i  E. alpinus} has been confused with{\b  9} and {\b 12} and intermediates with both these occur. Like {\b 9} it is closely related to {\b 11}, from which it is best distinguished by the usually dense crispate indumentum and acute basal leaves. Records of {\b 7} from S. Spain (Sierra Nevada) mostly refer to{\b  13}.
